Test Date Picker Accessibility with a Screen Reader

04
On this page
  1. Testing Date Grid Accessibility with VoiceOver
  2. The Date Picker Key Gotcha

We’ve made some significant changes to the date picker so it’s time to check our work with screen readers.

Testing Date Grid Accessibility with VoiceOver

Since we adjusted the markup, the Tab key allows us to reach and operate the buttons which we couldn’t do before.

Opening up VoiceOver with Fn + CMD + F5 , notice that the previous and next months are announced as “Less than June, button”. This is a bit jarring, so we’ll fix it in a later lesson.

As for the date buttons, VoiceOver is able to read out more context than only the numbers thanks to the ARIA we added.

One thing to note is that toggling the aria-pressed state on the button does not trigger immediate feedback from VoiceOver. As it currently stands, the user would have to Tab past the button then come back to it be informed that the state has changed.

The important thing is that we now have introduced programmatic accessibility information into the date picker.

The Date Picker Key Gotcha

In the last challenge, we updated the markup of the date picker key to use an unordered list.

When we check it with Safari and VoiceOver, it strips away the semantic information that tells it the items it’s announcing are a list. That was the whole point of changing the key to use the <ul> in the first place!

VoiceOver does this because it’s relying on the presence of bullet styles, which we don’t have.

We can fix this by adding the explicit role="list" to the <ul>:

<ul className="date-key" role="list">
<ul className="date-key" role="list">

There is a chance that after making this change that some accessibility testing tools will tell us that we’ve added an explicit role that we don’t need. But it’s better to have the screen reader work as intended than it is to leave it off to make a tool happy.
